                <head>177. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>The closing of the Suez Canal after Egyptian President <persName
                        corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName>’s nationalization of the Suez Canal
                    Company on July 26, 1956, adversely affected Denmark, Norway, and Sweden; none
                    had an indigenous oil supply and each was heavily dependent upon oil for
                    industry, agriculture, and domestic heating. Each government requested the
                    United States to cooperate in existing plans, put forward by the Organization
                    for European Economic Cooperation, for the allocation of oil in Europe.
                    Documentation on Scandinavian attitudes on this question is in Department of
                    State, <gloss target="#t_BNA1">BNA</gloss> Files: Lot 59 D 21 and Lot 58 D 399.
                    Norwegian Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_LHM1">Halvard Lange</persName>
                    discussed the Middle East <pb facs="0537" n="499" xml:id="pg_499"/> situation
                    and the oil problem with Acting Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1"
                        >Hoover</persName> on November 30. A memorandum of their conversation is <hi
                        rend="italic">ibid.,</hi> Central Files, 611.57/11–3056. Extensive
                    documentation on the crisis, including the question of possible oil shortages in
                    Western Europe, is in volume XVI.</p>
            </div>
